EXCITED to finally share my work with @adobe @adobestock

Apparently it’s #nationalpancakeday and I just made a boatload of pancakes that are #glutenfree and #dairyfree for weekday breakfasts. 

Photo of pancakes plus syrup; but something got me thinking lately - How often do you really see representation of diverse voices/faces in the photo industry when you look around? Representation with speakers who have great talent, event planners, stylists, makeup artists, designers, or even attendees from all walks of life? Do you make an effort to not just show #diversefaces in your #portfolio (if you don’t yet, please do) but also see how to incorporate diversity in your everyday life? 

I can give an entire talk about this topic; just saying since I’ve written about this too :) 

We all have unique voices no matter where we come from and just as learning a new genre enriches our creativity; at least trying to take a step towards understanding another culture, their experiences, thoughts and opinions - can surprisingly change the way you approach your art, or even better - enrich your life in ways you didn’t even think was possible!

There’s something about taking a trip by yourself or for yourself that inspires you to find beauty and creativity back again. Growing up, I was a quiet kid, teen and never knew how to express myself fully. I wrote poems a little here and there (that were mostly inspired by #bollywood) but it never quite fit well until I found photography. I had the need to be surrounded by people all the time; but never fully liked interacting with everyone except a select few friends. The crowd helped me disappear…It took me to be an adult to fully learn and love being alone in my own company (being alone and lonely are two different things :) 

Do you enjoy your own company? How often do you spend time getting away creating on your own taking creative breaks? 

I chat about many discussions that help bring out your creative self like these in my 4 week creative workshop @clickphotoschool - The Imperfectionist.

I’ve written and erased my caption a few times. The world is shifting..Women are being represented more in spaces you haven’t normally see them...(we’ve been here all the time though!!) and there’s a LONG way to go yes; but appreciating we are taking strides. 

It was 2005 Jan I was hired for my first ever full time job as an Electrical Engineer in Auckland, New Zealand. I was in the construction industry; and the 2nd woman in our 100 ppl MEP firm working as a new hire and I remember seeing a female role model, at that time who was 30; had young kids and wrapping up her masters and dressed professionally, handling work like a pro. She was a mentor; my first mentor in fact in my career ever. She was a Muslim woman from Iran. (I’ll tell you in a minute why this matters). She inspired me to keep going. That keep doing you; and things will follow. I remember going to my first ever construction site visit and being this terrified 21 yr old brown woman amongst men twice my size waiting for instructions on what needed to be done next in the project I was working on…needless to say I was intimidated. 

I may not be in the same industry now after 14 yrs but a lot of that translates over. I’m extremely thankful for people who believed in me while I transitioned into a new industry 10 years ago. Friends and connections that were genuine, retreats and spaces that hired me to speak because I wasn’t just a checkbox as a person color, or a woman. Mentors that went out of their way and time to welcome me into their space and circles to make introductions. 

While this industry may still appear to be male dominated heavily; we are making strides. Representation means having woman take the stage, speak, write, teach at places where decisions happen, women of all abilities, color, race everyone being inclusive. When you see someone who looks like you; you know you are being included.

the textures and the space, 
the body movement and shapes 
is all a part of being an artist, a photographer who is present. 

Be it natural light or 
adding that extra bit of artificial light to make your subjects pop is an artistic decision one has to make when you are the artistic director at a shoot. 

Creative techniques don’t have to be expensive 
or expressed through over processing. 
Knowing your way around your equipment 
and being present is enough. 

Organically flowing through your shoot 
with intention than posing someone through 
and through can yield a completely different feel, emotions in the images, or stories you are looking to tell.

*Vulnerable post*// I have been doing self portraits for over 6 years now. When I started self portraiture I really wanted to get better at my technical skill set along with documenting mostly motherhood (hiding behind my kid because I hated how I felt after having diastisis recti) and generally felt tired all the time. For more than two decades now I’ve struggled with anxiety, sometimes severe enough that I have to stop everything I’m doing and focus on my breathing (got worse after my divorce 11 years ago). As a teen I remember being bullied by my classmates about how I looked (had short hair and was very skinny) and that was something I took with me as an adult for a very long time. Even today, I always imagine and dream the worse possible outcomes with everything I do - the obvious imposter syndrome that affects many of us photographers. 

You see, confidence is an internal thing. Not to be shattered or changed by an external thing/person. I wish I could go back to tell my teen self to F all those negative comments, or cared less back in the day of what people thought of me. I wish I picked up photography earlier in life more seriously…

All those decades of negative self talk translated to anxiety, although now as a 41 yr old although I care much less about what people think/say (except my clients of course!). 

Anxiety is real feeling/something we all go through as kids, teens or adults at some point in our lives and I hope we learn to find ways to cope with it..to me, #selfportraiture was what saved me. #anxietyawareness // Do you have a friend, a family member you know who might be struggling with anxiety too? Perhaps just talking to them is all what they might need…

I’m forever thankful for all the accolades and accomplishments but being entirely self taught I still struggle with imposter syndrome the most. 

While we all share our end of the year successes, there were many I didn’t make it through as well. That grant I wanted really bad to fund a personal project, that commissioned project for @nytimes , lost two big projects that I was being considered for initially and a few more. You see, it’s never an easy straight path, but you’ve got to persevere, never take no for an answer, celebrate your wins, and keep learning something new at every phase of your journey including from what you didn’t win. 

Remember to never compare yourself with someone who started 10 years ago than you or someone who already has a leg in the commercial world based on who they are or who they know :) Still learning that one! 

One thing that I took away this year that I heard being said from the @therevworkshop was - “Why not me?”- that’s my goal coming into 2024.
